{"/service/ndnp/vtu/batch_vtu_charlotte_ver01/data/sn86072143/00280777201/1908052801/0351.xml":{"full_text":"THK Hi J Iv-LLiNU ION KKBW PKKS8 THURSDAY. MAY 28. 1 U08.\nT-3\nd or tlie crew Is now on tlm Island,\nnnd we know whnt that slcnlnVs.\"\n\"Is there no ohunoo of lirlbltiR tlipfft\npeople- Into friendliness op at least Into\na temporary trure?\"\n\"It Is hard to decide. Tollomnelie\nand Sunrez arc- best nlilo to fonn an\nopinion. What do you smy, Tolle\nmacho J\"\n\"Not n bit of use. They are insntlu\nhit. The more you Rive the more they\nwant. Tho only way to deal with\nthose rotters Is to stir them up with i\nGattliiK or n twelve pounder.\"\nRuarez when appealed to shook his\nhead.\n\"You mlfiht ns well try to fondle ,'t\nhungry puma. I am the only man they\nhave ever spared, and they spared me\nsolely because they tbotiRht 1 Rae\nthem power over their eneinlc. If\nyou had n cannon you mlcht drive\nthem off. As It Is, we shall he com\npelled to fifth t for our live. They arc\nbrave enough In their own way.\"\nThe experience of the mlaer from\nArgentina was not to lie gainsaid.\nCourtenay glanced up at Klsle. If\ntight were needed to complete the\ncontrast between civilization nnd sav\nagery It was given by the comparison\nwhich the girl offered to the women In\nthe canoe. The hot snn and the nli\nsence of wind had changed the tem\nperature from winter to summer. Aft\ner breakfast Klsle hud donned a mus\nlin dress and a broad brimmed straw\nhat. lixposnre to the vent her had\nbron&od her skin to a delightful tint.\nHer nut brown li.'ilr framed a sweetly\nprcttj face, and her clear blue eyes\n1 SgSJgi\nElsie setictl the chnncr of snapehatttnq\nthe part.\nand red lips, slightly parted, smiled\nbewUchlngly at the men beneath. The\ncamera In her hands added a holiday\naspect to her appearance, an aspect\nwhich was unutterably disquieting in\nits relation to the muttered forebod\nings she had broken In on.\n\"I find the get-up of our visitors dis\ntinctly humorous,\" he said, \"and I\nhope ther are a bit seared of us. VW\nwould prefer their room to their com\npany.\" \"I thought that Senor Suarez would\nbail them, as he can speak their lan\nguage. Perhaps he does not wish them\nto know he is on board?\"\nNow, Elsie, hart heard the man's im\npassioned appeal when the Indians\nwere first sighted, so Courtenay felt\nthat she, too, was acting.\nA new direction was given to Elsie's\nthoughts by the somewhat scowling\naspect of Chrlstobal's face. He was\nlooking at Courtenay in a manner\nwhich betokened certain displeasuie.\nThe Spaniard's cultivated cynicism\nwas subjugated by a more powerful\nsentiment. It seemed to KNIo that he\nenvied Courtenay his youth and high\nspirits.\nElsie dared not meet Courtenay'.i\neye. A flood of understanding had\nsuddenly poured its miraculous waters\never her, Incidents unimportant in\nthemselves, utterances which seemed\nto have no veiled Intent at the time,\nrushed In upon her with overwhelming\nconviction. The middle aged physician\nsuspected her of flirting with Courte\nnay and disapproved of It iih strongly\nas she herself had condemned Isobel's\nadmitted efforts In the same direction,\nThe proceedings of the Indians put\nstop to any further conversation. The\ncanoe had drifted closer to the ship.\nIt was about eighty yards distant when\nthe Indian who was on his feet sud\ndenly whirled a sling and bent a stone\ncrashing through the window of tip;\nmusic room. The heavy missile, which\nwhen picked up was found to weigh\nnearly half a pound, Just rulsed Tolle\nmache. The captain raised a double barreled\nfowling piece, the only gun on board,\nnnd tired point blank at the savages.\nBut the women were paddling away\nvigorously, and the shot splashed In\nthe water on nil sides of the canoe,\nthough a howl nnd a series of violent\ncontortions showed that one at least\nof the pellets had stung the wizened\nIndian whom Punrez believed to be n\nnewcomer.\nTlipre was no second shot cartridges\nwere too precious to be wasted at an\nImpossible range-but the undeniable\nfact remained that the Indlnus meant\nto be nggresslve. For n little time no\none spoke. They heard the echoes of\nthe gunshot faintly thrown back by\nthe nearest wall of rock. The regular\nplash of the paddles as the ennoo sped\nshoreward was distinctly audible. They\nwatched the tiny craft, until it vanish\ned round the wooded point which con\ncealed Otter creek.\nThe muflled clang of a hammer broke\nthe .llni: which had fallen on the.\nwnt\"hevs rrom the ship. Walker had\nlipped back to his beloved englues.\nHad ho not vowed that tho niastrtve\npistons should again thrust forth their\nwilling arms on or about New Year's\nday? Uh had forgotten the ranulbals\nnnd their threats ere ho was at the.\nfoot of the engine room ladder, C'ourte\nttfiy nud Tollemaehe Joined him; Chris\nfol.nl went to the salon to visit his\npatients; Klsio was left with Mr. noyle,\nwho forthwith fell Into a doze, being\nworn out by the fresh air and tho excitement.\nJoey, having followed Courtenay to\nthe one doorway In the ship which he\ncould not enter, trotted bnck to llud\nElsie. She greeted him with enthu\nsiasm. \"Hull, friend,\" rIip said. \"You at\nleast are not Jealous If I speak to your\nmaster, wherein you show your ex\nceeding wisdom. Now, since you nnd\nI are persons of leisure, tell me, Joey,\nwhat we shall do to make ourselves\nuseful.\"\nThe dog was noenstomed to being\nspoken to. Ho awaited developments.\n\"It seems to me, Joey,\" she contln\nued, \"that Gugllelmo Erascuelo Is the\none person on board who claims out\nattention. There Is n mystery to 1\nsolved, Round up In It arc my poor\nIsobel, that beast Ventnna nnd a\ndrunken conl trimmer--an odd assort\nincut to rub shoulders, don't you\nthink?\"\nJoey sflll reserved his opinion. When\nthe girl went to the forecastle by climb\ning down the sailors' ladder to the low\ner deck he thought she was making a\nmistake, but she held her nrms for his\nspring, and nil was well. She had not\npreviously visited the quarters set\napart for the crew. Puzzled by the\nlarse number of small cabins with\nmimes of subordinate officers painted\non them, she paused nnd cried loudly:\n\"Are you there, I'rnscuelo? May I\nspeak to you?\"\nAn exclamation of surprise, a some\nwhat forcible exclamation, too, answer\ned her from an Inner berth. Eras\ncuelo had heard from ihe Chilean who\nbrought his meals that there was an\nEnglishwoman on board, but he did\nnot know that she spoke Spanish flu\nently. Kraseuelo was reclining on a lower\nbunk. His Injured leg was well on the\nway toward recovery, but the wound\nanil Its resultant confinement hart\nchastened him. He hart lost the brig\nandish swagger which was his most\ncherished asset.\nAfter acknowledging inquiries as to\nhis progress he showed such eagerness\nfor news that Elsie told him briefly\nwhat had caused the latest uproar.\nShe cheered him, too, with the an\nnouncement made by the engineer nnd\nthen led him to the topic on which she\nsought information.\n\"In some ways 1 regard you as most\nunfortunnte,\" she said. \"I have been\ntold yon are here by accident: thnt you\nnever meant to take the voyage at all.\nIs that tnie'r\"\nFrascuelo. delighted to have secured\na sympathetic listener, poured forth\nhis sorrows volubly. He bore no ill\nwill against the captain, he said. He\nknew It was wrong to draw a knife on\nthe chief oflker, as his tale was an\nunlikely one, nnd he ought to have\ntrusted to n more orderly recital of the\nfarts to obtain credence.\n\"But I was that mad, senorita, I Just\nsaw red, and the drink was yet surg\ning up In me. I felt I must fight some\nbody, whatever the consequences.\"\n\"Can you tell me why any one had\nsuch n grlvace against you that you\nshould he thrown Into the hold and\nnearly killed? That was a strange\nthing to do, especially as you came\naboard too late for your work.\"\n\"Ah, that is the point, senorita. You\nsee, we trimmers work in gangs, and\nthe man who flung me through tho\nhatch was the man who had taken ny\nplace. I see no reason to doubt that It\nwas lie who made me drunk the previ\nous evening, and I know who did\nthat.\"\n\"What was his name?\"\n\"Jose Anacleto Mose the Winebag'\nwe call him on the plaza. I ought to\nhave smelted mischief when Jose paid.\nNever before had I seen him do such\na thing. And a good liquor too. nios,\nit must have cost him dollars.\"\n\"What object had he in coming on\nboard instead of you?\"\n\"All, there you beat me, senorita. I\nhave twisted my poor brain with think\ning of that. We only earned a dollar\na head, and bunkering n ship from a\nflat is hard work while It lasts, where\nas one would expect Jose to ride twen\nty miles the. other way to cc-ipo such\na task. Itut he was In the plot, nnd he\nstinll tell me why or\"\nUy force of habit 1'rasowln put ills\nright hand to his licit, bin hN sheath\nknife had been taken from him He\nsmiled sheepishly, yet his black eyes\ntwinkled.\n\"I'lot! Why do you speak of a plot?\"\nasked the girl, hoping tlm' the word\nbetokened some more promising clew\nthan she could discern thus far.\n\"Why did the furnaces blow up?\nTrll me that and 1 can answer you.\nCood, honest coal Isn't made of gun\npowder. Jose or some one behind him\nmeant to sink the ship, nnd as I\nmight have proved awkward they were\nwilling that I should go down with\nher. Mnybe I shall meet Jose If we\nget out of this rat trap. Then we shall\nhave a little talk.\"\nDespite the man's shrewd guess as\nto the cause of the accident in tho\nstokehold Elsie was at a loss to con\nnect the freak of some Valparaiso loaf\ner with the deep laid scheme wnlch\ncontemplated the destruction of the\nKansas. She' had followed the discus\nslon in the chart room with full appre\nciation of its significance. Valuable\nas the ship nnd cargo were, there wns\nfar more at stake In the effect of the\nloss on the copper markets of the\nworld. The most important cupper ex\nporting firm in Chile would practically\nbe mined, while tlie Talis \"ring,\" or\nwhich she had read in the newspapers,\nwould have matters its own way.\nFinancial interests of such magnitude\nwould hardly be bound up with the\ncarousniu and quarrels of Frascuela\nand \"Jose the Winebag.\" Yet\n\"Have you ever heard of Senor P\ndro Ventana,\" she asked suddenly.\n\"Has he to do with mines?\" inquired\nths Chilean tentatively.\n\"Yes.\"\n\"I know him by sight, senorita.\"\n\"Would he be acquainted with this\nman Anacleto, do you think?\"\n\"Can't sny, Jose would know any\nbody whom he could touch for n few\npesetas.\"\nShe left him, promising to visit him\ndally in tho future. As she walked\nback toward the bridge companion\nsho met Dr. Chrlstobal. His fit of 111\nhumor had gone. lie was nil smiles,\nbut Elsie, having extracted such In\nformation as Frascuelo possessed, wns\nbent on adding to her store of knowl\nedge. Incidentally she meant to widen\nthe doctor's views.\n\"Why have you taken to lecturing\nme?\" she asked, with a simple direct\nness which Chrlstobal was not slow\nto profit by.\n\"Because, though old enough to be\nyour father, 1 have not yet reached\nyears of discretion.\"\n\"You mean, I suppose, that if everj\none attended to one's own affairs II\nwould be n los spiteful world? I aro\nlucllned to agree with you, I'nhappl'\nly life Is largely made up of these\nminor evils. Yet I should have thought\nthat the desperate conditions under\nwhich we exist at this hour might pro\ntect me from unchnrltnbleness.\"\n\"You are pleased to be severe.\"\n\"No; It Is the Inst privilege of dan\nger that shams should vanish. Yet\nwe plumb the depths of absurdity\nwhen we contest the right of any wo\nman, even a young nnd unmarried one,\nto nppreclnte all that n brave man has\ndone and Is doing to save her life.\"\nElsie was speaking without heat, j\nShe might have been reasoning some\ndisputed point in ethics. The Span\nlard was obviously thrown off his\nguard.\n\"You seem to demand an explana\ntion,\" he said, with some warmth.\n\"Well, you shall have It. I am not a\nman to flinch from the disagreeable. I\nnrtinlt a tort of IniptosMnn, I might al\nmost describe It as a conviction, that\nCaptnln Conrtcnny's manner toward\nyou betokens a growing admiration.\n\"This Is the wildest folly,\" cried\nElsie In bewilderment. \"I-1 cannot\nimagine what put such a notion Into\nyour head.\"\n\"Let me at least lay claim to a spe\ncies of altruism.\" he replied. \"I can\nsee lift excellent reasons why our\nyoung nnd good looking commander\nshould lie drawn to you, nor can I urge\none against it.\"\n\"Hut he is already engaged to an\nother womnn, so my one reason Is\nworth more than all your fifty.\"\n\"All. can that really be so?\"\nThe tense eagerness In his voice\nmight have warned her were It not\nthat she was shocked by the bitterness\nwhich welled up In her heart. She\nwas amazed by this Introspective\nglimpse. It alarmed her. She must\nconvince herself at all costs that she\nhad spoken truly.\nAlthough the evidence she tendered\nwas of dubious value, she strove to ad\nvance her argument further.\n\"I have prized our friendship great\nly. Dr. Chrlstobal.\" she said, speaking\nwith a calm dellbcrnteness that rang\nhollow In her own ears, \"so greatly\nthat I am compelled to utter this pro\ntest. Now, to end a distasteful con\ntroversy let me tell you what I know\nto bo true. When the ship was strand\ned and we nil thought our only chance\nof safety wns to take to the boats, by\nn fluke, the accident of tlie moment, 1\nwas left alone in the captain's cabin.\nTlie sea was breaking In through the\ndoorway, and It brought an odd relief\nto my overburdened mind when I en\ndeavored to rescue the contents of a\nlocker which for some reason had\nbeen scattered on the floor previously.\nAmong them I found some letters. I\nthink you will believe me when I say\nthat I would not consciously read an\nother person's private correspondence.\nJust then I was hardly responsible for\nmy actions, and I did happen to see\nnud grasp the meaning of a passage in\na letter from Captain Courtenay's sis\nter which alluded to his affianced\nwife. It is not such a tragic admission,\nis it? I would scarce have given It an\nother thought were it not for your\nmanner this morning and your words\nlast night. I paid no heed at the time\nto the Innuendo that. I had come on\ndeck to find him to waylay him, as I\nhave heard men say when speaking of\na type of woman 1 despise. So I re\nsolved to straighten out a stupid little\ntangle. It would be ridiculous in our\npresent state of suspended animation\nto let such a slight thing mar our\nIrlendshlp.'\nElsie wns Indulging in that most de\nlusive thing, self persuasion. It was\nnot surprising, therefore, thnt she failed\nto note the unmixed satisfaction with\nwhich Christohal listened.\n\"Am I forgiven, then?\" he asked,\nwith a new tenderness in his voice.\n\"Oh, yes; let us laugh at It.\"\nnut\"\n\"riea.se let us talk of something\nmore useful. I have a little plan, and\nyou might ask the captnln if he ap\nproves of it. We have plenty of strong\ncanvas. 'Vhnt do you say If I set to\nwork and cover In the promenade deck\nfore and aft as well as both sides?\nThen If the Indians try to seize the\nship they would not be able to gain a\nlodgment at so many points simul\ntaneously. It would simplify the de\nfense, so to speak\n\"Admirable; I am sure Courtenay\nwill agree. Indeed, I nm ashamed that\nwe superior males failed to hit on tho\nIdea earlier. Before I go let me bt\ncertain that ray forgiveness is com.\nplete.\"\n\"Shall we quarrel about a degree of\nblessedness? I assure you I like you\nmore than ever. When all is said and\ndone, you thought I was flinging my\nself nt our excellent captain's brad, so\nyou tried to spare me the pangs of un\nicqultert Jove.\" The vtonls hurt, but\nshe did ffl flinch. Chrlstobal, anxious\nto decehe himself, wns radiant.\n\"Your charity goes too far.\" lie cried,\n\"That was not the exact reason. No,\nmy dear Miss Maxwell; I begin to ex\nercise a newborn discretion. I shall\nnot elucidate that cryptic remark un\ntil after New Year's day. But I don't\nmind telling you why I have hit ol a\ndefinite dale. If all goes well with us\nand vte have had so many escapes\nthat Providence may well send us a\nfew more- the Kansas should Nteam\nout of our little bay of (Jood Hope\nabout that period. Then I shall remind\nyou of our discussion and keep my\npromise.\"\nWith that he left her. After a gasp\nor two of surprise, for Elsie could read\nonly one meaning into his words, she\nhurried up the bridge companion to\narouse Mr, Boyle nnd ask what h\nwould like for luncheon.\n(Ti nr. roNTiNiiRn).\nANTICIPATION.\nOnly on more month of school,\nThen the barefoot days anri conl;\nThen the sunshine nnd the rain,\nIn the ehlldheart land again!\nOnly one more month of hooks,\nThen the bloomy forest nooks;\nThen the hubhle and the dream,\nAnfi the good old fishing stream!\nBaltimore Sun.\nALL AFTER THE PRESIDENT\nWoodruff Trying to Get Senator\nPiatt's Place.\nNew York Male Leaders Combine\nMoose clt Will .Xante fnnrilrinte\nror !eonr, Untermir nnd\nVice-President.\nA new political came In New York Is\nthus defected by the Washington cor\nrespondent of th Hrooklyn Ragle;\nFollowing th mysterious visit of Tim\nothy Woodruff to tho White House\non Sunday there has heen t,n(1 of\npolitical gossip among New York republi\ncans regarding the successor of Senator\nT. C. Plntt, the gubernatorial nomina\ntion and the selection of a New Yorker\nas n running mate for Secretary Tnft\non the national tleket. .naturally the\nWhite House the storm centre of this\nf peculation, a la ran part of which con\ncerns the quest ion of who shall fall heir\nto I'latt's senatorial toga.\nNational Committeeman, William I..\nWind wits at the White House, mi are.\nex-Congressman I.uclus UttriUM'\nand J. Sloat Fasett. Ex-Stnte Cliilrman\nGeorge Dunn saw the. President on Sit.\nurdny.\nWoodruff's talk with the Pre-lrient\nSunday night nnd the supposition th.it\nt ho senators!) p wns dlsrlsseri hns had\ntho effect of bringing a large flork of\nrival candidates Into tlie fir hi. .Msi a\nsuarp fight h-i\" hen anticipated between\ncandidates from the Northern ntid South\nern sections of the. state.\n\"Woodruff need not think he Is going\nto get I'latt's job,\" remarked an aspliant\nfor senatorial honors from one of the up\nper counties \"The next senator\nwill be an up-State nnn. It would nerr\ndo to have senators from the city\nof New York.''\nAs a result n' the ,me that i.as 1 n\ndrawn between the up-State and down\nState men the candidates may be lined\nup as follows:\nDown-State ipen, Stite Chairman Tim\nothy 1,, Woodruff and Concreinan !Ier\nbert Parson\"\nCp-State men Const e.mati James S.\nSherman. Congressman J .Sloat CneM,\nCongressman .lames R Perkm-, ex-Con-Bressman\nI.. N l.lttnner. K. II .Htitler of\nBuffalo anil rx-;overnni Crank .VI. Hlnek.\nThere are Mfns of an understanding\namong the up state men to prevent the\nsenatorshlp go.ng to a man from the\nlower sertlnn \"f the State. The Inten\ntion of .ourse v to brat oo Iruff. who\nIs looked upon as the noM formidable\nof the candidates from tlm nunrt.r now\nIn the field oi being er.oiily talked\nabout. Woodruff has hanked on going to\nl..c Senate ever since he accepted the\nState chairmanship two years ago. It Is\nn.erted. however, thst there w.i no\ncondition that h should succeed Piatt\nwhen he took tn Job. Senator Piatt is\nhimself respons Me. for the statement\nthat Parsons Is a candidate for the Sen\nate. Friends of the latter as-ert thit\nParsons Is not in avowed mndida'e.\nThe also siy that Parsons' choice is\nEllhti Root Fassett i regarded as\nPUlt's candidate, the latter having stateil\non several occasions that he considered\nFassett his !ega'e, so far as the sena\ntorhlp wa conr-rned\nApparently eve candidate Is angling\nfor the suppart .f the President It is\nconcede on ever' hand that hl recom\nmendation will be -tifTi-ient to dlpoe of\nthu matter. One candidate even went so\nfar as to sky: \"There a no use\ndenying- the Influence exerted b the\nPresident In New York State polltbs.\nThere Is no douht In my mind that hi;\nwill name the candidates for enntor,\ngoeinor, and for I (-president. pro\nvided It turn out that Taft' running\nmate Is to come from our State.\"\nJim Sherman hns expressed a prefer\nence for the govet norri'p over a place\nIn the Senate. Hlnek'x \"barrel head\"\nspeech is regarded by his friends as elim\ninating him from the en.itorshlp beou-e\nIt eat ned for him th? r erlii.sting enmity\nof the White House. There l.s much talk\nof the nomination of Speaker Wadworth\nfor irovernor.\nIt will he seen fcom th'\" gossip that\nthe slate makers ate not making very\nmany plans for providing CJmcrnor\nHughes with a political berth this fall.\nSome believe that he w ll be n cnndldate\nfor re-ecctlon, but ns a general tiling\nhe Is left out of their \"peculations, ap\nparently on the theor that his Piesi\ndentiul boom is hopeless, that lv- does\nnot want the vice-presidency nnd will\nnot i-eek a second tiim If he gets his\nanti-lacing bill through at tlie extra\nsei-.s.on.\nThere are a lot of things to keep tlie\nNew York politicians guessing and a\nvast amount of theorizing Is being In\ndulged In. In addition to tlie foregoing\nfat plums to be figured on at leaM one\ncabinet portfolio In the Taft adminis\ntration. Accounts differ regarding the exact\npurpose on Woodruff's lsit to the Pies,\nirienl. Before going to tlie White House\nhe informed some of hl.s friends that ho\nhad b'.cn fcent for. After leaving the\nWhite House he nppeired to be in doubt\nas to the reason he had been summoned\nto Washington. The White House c\nport on the incident Is that it \"amounted\nto nothlnz.\"\nA NKW HO.Vnilftl.AMl,\n(From the New York Post.)\nIf Mr. Lewis Carroll wete alive, now he\nwould probibly take pleasure In writ\ning a book on Morocco. Things go by\nopposite\" In the land of two .Sultans,\nthree capitals, and one irod with Mo\nhammed as his prophet, in other coun\ntries, when a monarch Is driven from\nhis enpltal Ills csute Is suppore.i to be\non the decline, and when he marches\nback on his capital with an armed force\nhis fortunes aro supposed to be Improv\ning. In other countries when n pre\ntender Is defeated the throne Is strength\nened In the same degree, and when pre\ntender runs away the lawful ruler comes\nInto his own. Not so In Morocco. There,\na few month ajm, the Inhabitants took\nadvantage of the departure of Abd-el-AzIz\nfrom Fez, to proclaim his brother. Mulal,\nSultan In hi\" place. Abd-el-Aziz held\nquiet court st Rabat on the roast, allow\ned his brother a clear road and the\ncause of AM-el-Ar.l. prospered. Mulal\nHafld, on the other hand, succeeded In\nputtln severul small armies in the fleld,\nwon several small victories over Ills bro\nther's forces and finally ran away\nThereupon Ahd-cl-AzIz set out triumph\nantly for Fe. Ho Is on his way still,\nbut his army Is now reported to be ready\nto go over to Mulal llnlld, for the sole\nreason, apparently, that tha latter did\nrun away. So we have, In Morocco the\nFrench policy of pacific penetration by\nmeans of rapid-firing giins, based upon\nan nmicalilii iinder.stnndiiiK between\nFrance nnd Spain, whose soldiers have\ncome to blow. And, dually there is\nGermany, who watches Franca Jealous\nly because Oerninn trade In Morocco has\ndoubled since the lerlnnlng of French\nactivity; and in her desire to make the\nFrench task easier and to prevent F.urop\ncan complications, rlim.s th' bel' and\nshout-. \"Fire!'' whenever France makes\na decisive move\nnnrnT VS. FAITIT.\nI have, within thc'inst twenty year\nof my life, come out of uncertainty and\ndoubt Into a faith which is an ahsoltite\ndominating conviction of the truth nnd\nabout which 1 have not a shadow of\ndoubt. T have been Intlmntelv associated\nwith eminent scientific workers, have\nbeard them discuss the profonndest ques\ntions: have myself fncaced in scientific\nwork and so know the- value of such\nopinions, writ's Pr Howard A. Kelly\nin the June Appleton's. I mis once pro-\nio-inoiv riiMiiroeri in tue iraomnnai inuii\n.1\nIn which 1 had been brought up th.it of\na Protestant F.p!scopallan--by inroads\nwhich were made upon the honk of\nOencsls bv the higher critics I could not\nthen galns.iv them, not knowing Hebrew\nnor arrhaenlogv well, and to me, as to\nmany, to pull out one great prop was to\nmake the whole foundation uncertain.\nSo I floundered on for some years try\ning, as some of my higher critical friends\nare trying to-day. to continue to use the\nnible as the word of Ood and at the\nsame time holding It of composite\nauthorship, a ourloti and disastrous\npiece of mental gymnastics a bridge\nover the chasm 'eparating an older Bible\nloving generation from a newer Hlhle.\ncmanolpited race. I saw- In the Rook a\ngreat light and glow of heat, yet shher\ned out In the cold.\nOne day It occurred to me to see what\nthe hook had to say about Itself As a\nshort, but perhaps not the best method,\nI took a concordance nnd looked out\n.'Word\", when I found that It claimed\nfrom one end to the other to he the au\nthoritative word of God to man. I then\ntried the natural plan of taking it as\nmy text-book of religion, as I would use\na text-book in nnv science, testing It by\nsubmitting to its conditions. I found that\nChrist Himself invites men( John vll Kj\nto do this.\nriioirv xkkos xo comhin -Tin.x.\n(From the Vergennes Enterprise)\nA combination between Protity and\nMead Is the report that conies from\nRutland city, and the origin of the\nreport Is accredited to some of Mead's\nfriends, who realize that his chances\nfor the nomination are growing less\nand less eery dav, and his candidacy\nneeds some stimulus to kcp it from\nfalling out of existence. There are many\nstrong Frouty men who are enraged by\nthe leport of such a combination and\nwill not countenance it for one\nmoment. The Idea (if such a combination\nIs ludicrous, the i routy adherents say:\n\"We can e'.ect our candidate on his own\nmeilts. We expect to have a hard con\ntest and we don't want to be loaded\ndown by obstacles, or by trying to drag\nalong another candidate that has so\nmuch opposition light in his own baili\nwick.\nGov Prouty would never sanction such\na combination, and It would be a great\nlns to his Intetests If he did, for while\nbe might gain a few points In Rutland\ncounty, he would lose n great many In\nother counties, where the supporters of\nJudge Karnes are so numerous. Should\nhe select a min for the second plaoe he\nwould naturally want one progressive\nIn spirit and independent to act for the\nbest interest' of th public. The contest\nfor the governorship bids fair to bo close\nand exciting, Judging from the situation\na-s It exists In this county Zed Stanton\nhas always had many friends in Addison\ncounty, and fcom nil appearancles they\nhave not deserted him.\nFrom our point of view, the report\nof a combination looks like a Mead\nmovement entirely. He is confronted\nwith so much opposition In his own city\nthat he Is grasping every straw that\nhe can get hold of to rav himself, and\nIt wouldnt be at nil surprising if his\nfriends would advise him to withdraw\nfrom the contest. Addison county will\nsupport Judge Parnei. as a unit.\nOUR KALEIDOSCOPE.\nT3NTRANCF, FOR HIS MF.AbS.\n\"And he had the nerva to tell me,\" th\nthickened boarder was romnrklng. \"that\nIt was Impossible for me to get any\nthing Into my head\n\"He dosen't know what he's talking\nabout,\" declared his landlady.\n\"I should say not!\"\n\"No; he hasn't any Idea of ths amount\nof food you get Into It.\" Philadelphia\nTress.\nnRTOND TH K STYX.\nrluto had Introduced Wackforfl\nSuueers,\" said Iogrce, \"Vou and I, I\nbelieve, are two of the most celebrated\nof the old masters.\"\nHut Suueers, who had Just been com\npel