a.s been ver III, and in\nsense has had typhoid fever, but now\nw\ni ,MC letcr has entirelj eft the dlseaao\nI v...i.\nIs out, and the patient onI lemains sick\nand weak, so that permanent recovery\nIs only a. matter of time. How to qulckrn\nthat recovery in a healthy manner Is the\nproblem we are undertaking, and we\nbelieve In the power of encouragement\nby showing to the world at large that.\nconditions are fundamentally sound and\nhealthy, and that nothing now exists but\na lack of confidence to restore us to a full\nmeasure of prosperity such as existed\na jear ago. We are nuking an effort\nthrough the press and through other\nbusiness associations, and through the\ntraveling salesmen, to encourage the pec\npie to see the .sunshine that is clearly\nIn the patnway, nnd to bel'eve that things\nare very much better than most people\nthink they are. and that with the pres\nent crop prospects soon to be realized, If\nnothing unforsccn occurs in the Immedi\nate future, It is only o question of a very\nshort time until the dinner palls will\nagain lie full and the unemp!oed will\nagain he employed at fair wages, and\nthat there will be no reduction In wages\nof those already employed Wo believe\ntlifre s a great chains of sentiment with\nthe intelligent people of the t nlted\nStates, and that It I\" 'ncreasing very\nrapidly It therefore seems to us a inol\npropitious time to do what we can to en\ncoutage a quick return of prosperity, to\nthe great lneflt of the laboring man\nand to the benefit of all business Interests.,\nFundamentally, everything Is all right\nthe basis of our prosperity comes from\ntlie soil, and the products of the soil have\nnever had greater alue than at present.\nTlie outlook for crops Is marvelous!'\npromising. To lllutrat- the winter\nwheat crop which is firs; one of Import\nance that comes to our notice Is better\nthan eer before in the history of this\ncountry. Kansas reports a condition of\nlft\" on wlnter w heat omethln hereto\nfore unknown. When the lumber Inter\nests shut down, and the railroads laid ofT\na lot of their employes, a laree pro\nportion of them went Immediately to the\nfarmers, or planters, so that tnese tollers\nof the soil have, for the first time In\nmany years, had enough labor, and tho\nplanting Is still going on With a larger\nplanting that ever before gone into tlm\nground, and with favor.iblo weather, it\nseems leasonable to suppose that we may\nhave most excellent crops this year It\nlooks exceedingly probable. Therefore,\neverything, which is the rm-e of our pros\nperity Is rifht all thnt i necessary now\nIs to restore confidence so that th\nwheels of commerce begin to move again\nwith the same rapidity that they did a\nyear or two ago, when we were at the\nheight of our prosperity, and from which\nwo went in a wonderfully short time to\nn very low stage of depression and hard\ntimes.\n1TATK\nOK KI.lUNon\n(ilAKI.UTTH.\nnooT of\nWe, the subscribers, having been\nappointed by the Honorable Probate\nCourt for the District of Chittenden,\ncommissioners to receive, examine and\nadjust the claims and demands of all\npersons against the estate of Kleauor\nRoot late of Charlotte, in said\ndistrict deceased, and also all claims\nand demands exhibited In offset there\nto; and lit months from the day ot\nthe date hereof being allowed hy said\nCovrt for that rurpose. we do there\nfore hereby give notice that we will\nattend to the duties of our appoint\nment at the late residence of th de\nceased In Charlotte in said district,\non the first Saturdays of June and\nNovember, next, at 10 o'clock a. m., on\neach of ald davs.\nimted this 9th day of May. 10,\nTV. W. HIOBKK,\nGEORGE A. FOOTK.\n41; w-3t Commlsaloners.\nSTF.IMIKX P. GORDON'S F.sJTATK.\nSTATE OF VERMONT. District of\nGrand Isle, ss\nIn Probate Court holden at North\nHero. In and for said district, on the\nHth day of May. A. D. I90S.\nElla tir rum uoruon jiiromninui\ni e e.Vnte of Stephen P. Gordon,\n,,f rranA isle In said distric